<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-747-384  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 747 384.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 10 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Claris launches universal translator. (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Claris Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   XTND (Computer program) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSoftware PublishersSoftware packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CLARIS LAUNCHES UNIVERSAL TRANSLATOR SANTA CLARA, CALIFORNIA, U.S.A., 1989OCT 3 (NB) -- Claris Corporation has removed yet another barrier to businessintegration of more Macintosh computers by offering a file translation schemethat will enable its software, including MacWrite and MacDraw, to exchangefiles with IBMs and compatibles, Digital's VAX, and other Unix machines, andother mini and mainframe systems.andP;  Claris is promoting it as the universalfile translator and licensing it free of charge to developers.andM;Claris' new open architecture technology, called XTND, enables developers toextend the capabilities of Claris applications by letting the applicationsaccess external code.andP;  The developer's job is as easy as copying theappropriate translator file into the Macintosh system folder.andP;  What thismeans is that Claris programs operating on a network can import or exporttext, graphics, spreadsheets, or charts, to programs written in A/UX, Unix,MS-DOS, PS/2 and a variety of other operating systems.andM;The first Claris product to use the new technology is MacWrite II 1.1 whichreads and writes in some 24 file formats, including Microsoft Word PC,WordPerfect PC 5.0, and AppleWorks.andP;  The DataViz MacLink Plus filetranslator, also announced, adds another 8 file formats, including WordStar,XyWrite, and OfficeWriter, to the list of programs with which MacWrite canexchange files.andP;  DataViz' MacLinkPlus PC version 4.1 costs $199 and MacLinkPlus Translators - version 4.1, cost $199 and $169 respectively.andO;XTND-versions of MacDraw II and FileMaker II are due out shortly.andM;Among the developers licensing XTND is ON Technology, founded by Mitch Kapor,formerly head of Lotus.andP;  Kapor's firm is implementing XTND into its secret&quot;future products;&quot; Kapor makes this comment about the software scheme, &quot;Fromthe customer's viewpoint, XTND is a great solution.andP;  It helps applicationscommunicate better.andP;  At the same time it preserves and respects thecustomer's right to choose applications he wants to use.&quot;andM;(Wendy Woods/19891006/Press Contact: Renee Mathews, Claris, 408-987-7202)</TEXT></DOC>